ss="profile-email" /><label class="profile-free-signup"><input type="checkbox" name="free_signup" defaultChecked /> Sign up for the newsletter</label><input type="hidden" name="photo_url" /><input type="hidden" name="needs_photo" /><input type="hidden" name="token" /><div id="error-container"></div><button class="button primary " type="submit">Save &amp; Post Comment</button></form></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="modal popup out gone  "><div class="modal-table"><div class="modal-row"><div class="modal-cell modal-content"><div class="container"><button class="button modal-btn modal-exit-btn " type="button"><svg width="15" height="15" viewBox="0 0 15 15" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M1 1L7.75 7.75M14.5 14.5L7.75 7.75M7.75 7.75L14.5 1L1 14.5"></path></svg></button><div class="paywall modal-paywall"><h2 class="paywall-title">Only paying subscribers can comment on this post</h2><div class="paywall-cta"><a href="/subscribe?simple=true&amp;next=https%3A%2F%2Fdivinations.substack.com%2Fp%2Fquibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar%3Futm_source%3Ddigg&amp;utm_source=paywall&amp;utm_medium=web&amp;utm_content=355585" native><button class="button primary subscribe-btn " type="button">Subscribe</button></a></div><div class="paywall-login"><a href="/account/login?redirect=%2Fp%2Fquibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar%3Futm_source%3Ddigg&amp;email=&amp;with_password=" native>Already a paying subscriber? <b>Sign in</b></a></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="comment-list "><div class="comment-list-items"><div class="comment  "><div id="comment-149956" class="comment-anchor"></div><div id="comment-149956-reply" class="comment-anchor"></div><table class="comment-content"><tr><td class="comment-head"><div class="user-head "><a><div class="profile-img-wrap"><img src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_66,h_66,c_fill,f_auto,q_auto:good/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack.com%2Fimg%2Fanonymous-head.png" /></div></a></div></td><td><div class="comment-meta"><span class><a href="javascript:void(0)">Salil Dalvi</a></span><span><a href="/p/quibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar/comments#comment-149956" native>Apr 7</a></span><span class="highlight">Liked by Nathan Baschez</span></div><div class="comment-body"><p><span>quibi has 3 “consumer asks”</span></p><p><span>1-download the app</span></p><p><span>2-watch a lot of video</span></p><p><span>3-pay for the service</span></p><p><span>By locking itself to smartphones, quibi creates friction in the most important place: getting viewers to watch. </span></p><p><span>100% of quibi’s programming is new (no library or familiar brands). And so quibi has a massive marketing challenge ahead of it: explain what quibi is (at the service and brand level), communicate what shows are available, and consistently drive users back to the app.</span></p><p><span>While $500M is a lot of cash to commit to marketing, these are very hard things to execute. Apple TV+ provides a very useful point of comparison. With every conceivable advantage: distribution, App Store placement, massive content budget, and ubiquitous advertising, I would bet you that unaided awareness of Apple TV+ (“name 4 subscription tv offerings”) is below 10%, and I would further bet you that 95% of consumers could not name more than 1 show on the service. </span></p><p><span>Of course, katzenberg’s relationships and track record are legendary. But the bogey is far more than a content budget. I respect that quibi picked a single competitive dimension (quality shows) and put all of their armies in that territory. But unfortunately, they picked an incredibly conventional battleground: many companies are producing great shows. And they chose to fight in an exceedingly conventional way, with video only (no interactive features or meta content). And they chose to engage in this fight without even using every available piece of firepower (by limiting distribution).</span></p><p><span>Of course I may be very very wrong. But I do not think I am. Unless I see broader distribution, or some other path to ubiquity, quibi will, in the words of Ben Horowitz, have to roll a hard 6 to succeed. And unfortunately for quibi’s  investors, I don’t think it had to be this way. </span></p></div><div class="comment-actions"><span><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="like-button"><svg width="15" height="20" viewBox="0 0 15 20" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="animation"><path d="M1.73624 5.1145C2.43974 4.37137 3.37095 4 4.3036 4C5.23626 4 6.16745 4.37137 6.87097 5.1145L7.49949 5.77892L8.1227 5.11986C9.52973 3.63357 11.8557 3.6336 13.2627 5.11986C14.6698 6.60612 14.6698 8.98642 13.2627 10.4727C11.4639 12.3728 9.66583 14.2737 7.86703 16.1738C7.81927 16.2242 7.76183 16.2643 7.6982 16.2918C7.63456 16.3192 7.56606 16.3333 7.49683 16.3333C7.42761 16.3333 7.3591 16.3192 7.29547 16.2918C7.23184 16.2643 7.1744 16.2242 7.12664 16.1738L5.77904 14.7472L3.08384 11.8939L1.73624 10.4673C0.331003 8.98011 0.329213 6.60074 1.73624 5.1145Z" stroke="#999999"></path></svg><svg width="15" height="20" viewBox="0 0 15 20" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M1.73624 5.1145C2.43974 4.37137 3.37095 4 4.3036 4C5.23626 4 6.16745 4.37137 6.87097 5.1145L7.49949 5.77892L8.1227 5.11986C9.52973 3.63357 11.8557 3.6336 13.2627 5.11986C14.6698 6.60612 14.6698 8.98642 13.2627 10.4727C11.4639 12.3728 9.66583 14.2737 7.86703 16.1738C7.81927 16.2242 7.76183 16.2643 7.6982 16.2918C7.63456 16.3192 7.56606 16.3333 7.49683 16.3333C7.42761 16.3333 7.3591 16.3192 7.29547 16.2918C7.23184 16.2643 7.1744 16.2242 7.12664 16.1738L5.77904 14.7472L3.08384 11.8939L1.73624 10.4673C0.331003 8.98011 0.329213 6.60074 1.73624 5.1145Z" stroke="#999999"></path></svg> 2</a><div class="modal  out gone modal-free-signup "><div class="modal-table"><div class="modal-row"><div class="modal-cell modal-content"><div class="container"><button class="button modal-btn modal-exit-btn " type="button"><svg width="15" height="15" viewBox="0 0 15 15" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M1 1L7.75 7.75M14.5 14.5L7.75 7.75M7.75 7.75L14.5 1L1 14.5"></path></svg></button><h2 class="page-title">Sign up to like comment</h2><form action="/api/v1/free?nojs=true" method="post" noValidate class="form "><input type="hidden" name="first_url" /><input type="hidden" name="first_referrer" /><input type="hidden" name="current_url" /><input type="hidden" name="current_referrer" /><input type="hidden" name="referral_code" /><input type="hidden" name="source" value="like_button" /><div class="sideBySideWrap"><input type="email" name="email" placeholder="Type your email…" /><button class="button rightButton primary subscribe-btn " type="submit"><b>Subscribe</b></button></div><div id="error-container"></div><div class="subtle-help-text below-input"><a href="/account/login?redirect=%2Fp%2Fquibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar%3Futm_source%3Ddigg&amp;email=&amp;with_password=" native class="login-button">Login</a><a href="/privacy" target="_blank" native>Privacy</a><a href="/tos" target="_blank" native>Terms</a></div></form></div></div></div></div></div></span><span><a href="javascript:void(0)">Reply</a></span></div></td></tr></table><div class="more-replies-container"><a href="/p/quibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar/comments#comment-149956" class="more-replies">1 reply by Nathan Baschez</a></div></div><div class="comment  "><div id="comment-149730" class="comment-anchor"></div><div id="comment-149730-reply" class="comment-anchor"></div><table class="comment-content"><tr><td class="comment-head"><div class="user-head "><a><div class="profile-img-wrap"><img src="https://cdn.substack.com/image/fetch/w_66,h_66,c_fill,f_auto,q_auto:good/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack.com%2Fimg%2Fanonymous-head.png" /></div></a></div></td><td><div class="comment-meta"><span class><a href="javascript:void(0)">Jason Koss</a></span><span><a href="/p/quibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar/comments#comment-149730" native>Apr 6</a></span><span class="highlight">Liked by Nathan Baschez</span></div><div class="comment-body"><p><span>people may buy iPhones and Blue Bottle because they like nice things, but often the true or </span></p><p><span>at least supplemental reason for the purchase is that people, even more, like signaling that they like &amp; have nice things. it's hard to deny that compared to a majority of social media usage, having an iPhone with three camera lenses or pulling up to Blue Bottle, there is not an obvious status gain from having a Netflix login and consequently it does seem to be a differentiated paid professional entertainment service. </span></p><p><span>that being said, seemingly pure entertainment-vehicles actually do bleed into the status game when they allow people entry into culturally relevant conversations. there's watching the thing and then there's talking about the thing you watched with your friends, etc. </span></p><p><span>people pay for Netflix to be entertained but they're also paying for social capital.</span></p><p><span>Netflix, Instagram and Youtube all create culturally relevant content that people want to access, and IG &amp; YT do it cheap as dirt. Quibi needs to create these moments to gain enough paying users to return their $1.75B investment in content*. so basically, they intend to do this in a 6-10 minute container on a device that has no precedent for significant lean-back usage at that length and, even though they're not &quot;directly&quot; competing with Netflix, Amazon and Disney, their competition on the device is instead Facebook, Google and Bytedance.</span></p><p><span>the risk where Quibi runs out of $ before it's able to create these moments (high cost/min, low content selection), stacked on the bet of creating a new-ish consumption behavior, and then finally acknowledging the competitors in the market (regardless of which bucket) all makes me feel like the road ahead to success looks like something in between extremely difficult and impossible.</span></p><p><span>*without running the numbers or even diving into how and why Quibi chose it's pricing structure, it would be interesting to think more about your book to internet analogy and see how those markets size up against each other and how that hypothetical looks for Quibi financials </span></p></div><div class="comment-actions"><span><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="like-button"><svg width="15" height="20" viewBox="0 0 15 20" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="animation"><path d="M1.73624 5.1145C2.43974 4.37137 3.37095 4 4.3036 4C5.23626 4 6.16745 4.37137 6.87097 5.1145L7.49949 5.77892L8.1227 5.11986C9.52973 3.63357 11.8557 3.6336 13.2627 5.11986C14.6698 6.60612 14.6698 8.98642 13.2627 10.4727C11.4639 12.3728 9.66583 14.2737 7.86703 16.1738C7.81927 16.2242 7.76183 16.2643 7.6982 16.2918C7.63456 16.3192 7.56606 16.3333 7.49683 16.3333C7.42761 16.3333 7.3591 16.3192 7.29547 16.2918C7.23184 16.2643 7.1744 16.2242 7.12664 16.1738L5.77904 14.7472L3.08384 11.8939L1.73624 10.4673C0.331003 8.98011 0.329213 6.60074 1.73624 5.1145Z" stroke="#999999"></path></svg><svg width="15" height="20" viewBox="0 0 15 20" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M1.73624 5.1145C2.43974 4.37137 3.37095 4 4.3036 4C5.23626 4 6.16745 4.37137 6.87097 5.1145L7.49949 5.77892L8.1227 5.11986C9.52973 3.63357 11.8557 3.6336 13.2627 5.11986C14.6698 6.60612 14.6698 8.98642 13.2627 10.4727C11.4639 12.3728 9.66583 14.2737 7.86703 16.1738C7.81927 16.2242 7.76183 16.2643 7.6982 16.2918C7.63456 16.3192 7.56606 16.3333 7.49683 16.3333C7.42761 16.3333 7.3591 16.3192 7.29547 16.2918C7.23184 16.2643 7.1744 16.2242 7.12664 16.1738L5.77904 14.7472L3.08384 11.8939L1.73624 10.4673C0.331003 8.98011 0.329213 6.60074 1.73624 5.1145Z" stroke="#999999"></path></svg> 1</a><div class="modal  out gone modal-free-signup "><div class="modal-table"><div class="modal-row"><div class="modal-cell modal-content"><div class="container"><button class="button modal-btn modal-exit-btn " type="button"><svg width="15" height="15" viewBox="0 0 15 15" fill="none" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M1 1L7.75 7.75M14.5 14.5L7.75 7.75M7.75 7.75L14.5 1L1 14.5"></path></svg></button><h2 class="page-title">Sign up to like comment</h2><form action="/api/v1/free?nojs=true" method="post" noValidate class="form "><input type="hidden" name="first_url" /><input type="hidden" name="first_referrer" /><input type="hidden" name="current_url" /><input type="hidden" name="current_referrer" /><input type="hidden" name="referral_code" /><input type="hidden" name="source" value="like_button" /><div class="sideBySideWrap"><input type="email" name="email" placeholder="Type your email…" /><button class="button rightButton primary subscribe-btn " type="submit"><b>Subscribe</b></button></div><div id="error-container"></div><div class="subtle-help-text below-input"><a href="/account/login?redirect=%2Fp%2Fquibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar%3Futm_source%3Ddigg&amp;email=&amp;with_password=" native class="login-button">Login</a><a href="/privacy" target="_blank" native>Privacy</a><a href="/tos" target="_blank" native>Terms</a></div></form></div></div></div></div></div></span><span><a href="javascript:void(0)">Reply</a></span></div></td></tr></table><div class="more-replies-container"><a href="/p/quibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar/comments#comment-149730" class="more-replies">1 reply by Nathan Baschez</a></div></div></div></div><a href="/p/quibi-will-be-a-multi-billion-dollar/comments" class="more-comments">25 more comments…</a></div></div><div></div><div class="subscribe-footer"><div class="container"><h1>Ready for more?</h1><form action="/api/v1/free?nojs=true" method="post" noValidate class="form "><input type="hidden" name="first_url" /><input type="hidden" name="first_referrer" /><input type="hidden" name="current_url" /><input type="hidden" name="current_referrer" /><input type="hidden" name="referral_code" /><input type="hidden" name="source" value="subscribe_footer" /><div class="sideBySideWrap"><input type="email" name="email" placeholder="Type your email…" /><button class="button rightButton primary subscribe-btn " type="submit"><b>Subscribe</b></button></div><div id="error-container"></div><div class="subtle-help-text below-input"></div></form></div></div></div></div><div class="footer-wrap"><div class="footer"><div class="container"><div>© 2020 Nathan Baschez. See <a href="/privacy" native>privacy</a> and <a href="/tos" native>terms</a></div><a href="https://substack.com/about?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=web&amp;utm_content=footer" native class="footer-substack-cta"><svg width="1000" height="1000" viewBox="0 0 1000 1000" fill="#FF6719" stroke-width="1" stroke="#000" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M764.166 348.371H236.319V419.402H764.166V348.371Z"></path><path d="M236.319 483.752V813.999L500.231 666.512L764.19 813.999V483.752H236.319Z"></path><path d="M764.166 213H236.319V284.019H764.166V213Z"></path></svg> Publish on Substack</a></div></div></div></div>
        </div>

        <script>
    (function () {
        var CLASS_NAME = 'balance-text';
        var LINE_HEIGHT_OFFSET = 10;
        var MAXIMUM_ERROR = 4;

        balanceDocument();
        window.balanceText = balanceText;
        window.addEventListener('load', balanceDocument);
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', balanceDocument);

        function balanceDocument() {
            if (!document.getElementsByClassName) return;
            var elems = document.getElementsByClassName(CLASS_NAME);
            for (var i = 0; i < elems.length; i++) {
                balanceText(elems[i]);
            }
        }

        function balanceText(elem) {
            if (isMultipleLines(elem)) {
                elem.style.maxWidth = '';
                squeeze(elem, elem.clientHeight, 0, elem.clientWidth);
            }
        }

        // Binary search for min width that doesnt require an extra line
        function squeeze(elem, originalHeight, min, max) {
            if (max - min < MAXIMUM_ERROR) {
                if (elem.clientHeight > originalHeight) {
                    elem.style.maxWidth = max + 'px';
                } else {
                    elem.style.maxWidth = (elem.scrollWidth + 1) + 'px';
                }
                return;
            }
            if (min >= max) {
                elem.style.maxWidth = max + 'px';
                return;
            }

            var mid = (min + max) / 2;
            elem.style.maxWidth = mid + 'px';
            if (elem.clientHeight > originalHeight) {
                squeeze(elem, originalHeight, mid, max);
            } else {
                squeeze(elem, originalHeight, min, mid);
            }
        }

        function isMultipleLines(elem) {
            // Save original text
            var html = elem.innerHTML;
            var words = elem.textContent.split(' ');

            // Wrap the first word
            var firstWord = document.createElement('span');
            firstWord.id = 'element-first-word';
            firstWord.textContent = words.shift();
            elem.innerHTML = '';
            elem.appendChild(firstWord);
            elem.appendChild(document.createTextNode(' ' + words.join(' ')));

            // Check the height of the first word
            var firstWordHeight = document.getElementById('element-first-word').offsetHeight;
            var elementHeight = elem.offsetHeight;

            // Restore original text
            elem.innerHTML = html;

            // Check if the block is taller than the first word (ie multi-line)
            return elementHeight - LINE_HEIGHT_OFFSET > firstWordHeight;
        }
    })();
</script>


        
        
